                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d627">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">881.00/8–2545: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fullerton</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-29T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 29, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4093. For Villard. Urtel 5153 Aug. 25, 2 p.m.<note n="79" xml:id="d627fn79">Not
                        printed.</note> Importance of having radiotelegraph station in Tangier as a
                    relay point to Eastern Europe, Near East and Far East cannot be too greatly
                    emphasized and right of US interests to establish such a station must, under no
                    circumstances, be jeopardized. However there is obviously no objection to
                    technical control of such stations such as that exercised by FCC<note n="80"
                        xml:id="d627fn80">Federal Communications Commission.</note> in this
                    country.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
